From 759391d986f80435da53245ea8b90878f7380b53 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 23 Jul 2026 11:35:58 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fov: mask nnunet_pred to the acquired FOV (no prediction in
 the truncated region)

nnUNet stage-1 runs on the FOV-truncated CT (out-of-FOV = air). At the truncation
boundary it under-segments AND spills foreground into the blanked region, but
there is no image evidence there -- so no prediction should exist. Zero every
nnunet_pred voxel outside that scan's visible_box, so the prediction (and its
visualization) carries no label in the truncated region, and CNISP's test-time
fit sees the clean "predicted-region" observation: it only optimizes where nnUNet
predicted (bg or fg) AND the image has data (= inside FOV). CNISP's loss mask is
already visible_box, so this makes the observation consistent with it.

Truncation preserves the CT grid, so the sidecar visible_box (source-voxel
windows) indexes the prediction voxels directly -- a pure voxel-window crop, no
affine/resampling; source_shape guards the grid match.

- nnunet-c/scripts/mask_nnunet_pred_fov.py: mask_pred_to_fov() + CLI (--config or
  explicit --pred-dir/--trunc-manifest) + --self-test.
- run_corrector_data.sh predict: auto-runs the masking when a FOV sidecar exists
  (gated, so the thick pipeline is untouched).

Re-run order after this: mask (or re-predict) -> align -> fov_pose_ab, so the
aligned obs patches are built from the FOV-masked prediction.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01GZk51Hdt9G9AuQAifPXdjG
